<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="64" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,526]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,267,293]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64">Etymology</emphasis>
. We name this species in memory of the Czech entomologist J. 
<collectingCountry box="[1084,1108,268,294]" name="Iceland" pageId="17" pageNumber="64">O</collectingCountry>
. Voříšek (
<date box="[1226,1363,268,294]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64" value="1921" valueMax="2008">
<number box="[1226,1363,268,294]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64" value="1964.5" valueMax="2008.0" valueMin="1921.0">1921–2008</number>
</date>
), with whom the senior author shared a personal friendship for more than 
<number box="[990,1020,306,332]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64" value="30.0">30</number>
years and whose kindness, warm hospitality and help with specimens and information was always inspirational.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="64" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,526]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,319,383,409]" pageId="17" pageNumber="64">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is easily recognisable by its comparatively smaller size, the barely convex elytra with faintly oblique declivity and vestiture of predominating brown scales with narrow stripes of whitish scales, the very long, flexible setae sparsely distributed over the entire dorsum, the long tufts of setae behind the base of the pronotum and the slightly shorter tarsal segments with long lateral setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
